      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Priya, it's really good that you're paying attention to how your body is responding to training — that kind of self-awareness is genuinely valuable, especially at this stage of marathon prep. Feeling low energy on long runs and lightheadedness after them are worth taking seriously, not brushing off.\n\nBefore I say anything else, I want to be upfront with you about where my expertise ends, because both of your questions touch on areas that deserve the right kind of help.\n\n---\n\n**On the iron supplements and lightheadedness:**\n\nThat combination — fatigue on long efforts and lightheadedness afterward — can have several different causes, and iron deficiency is one possibility worth investigating. But I'm a running coach, not a medical professional, and I genuinely can't tell you whether to take iron supplements. Taking iron without knowing your actual levels can cause real harm, and the only way to know is bloodwork.\n\nWhat I'd encourage you to do is book an appointment with your GP and ask specifically about a full blood panel — ferritin, hemoglobin, and B12 are all worth checking for endurance athletes. That gives you real information rather than guesswork. Once you have those results, you'll be in a much stronger position — and so will I, in terms of how we structure your training load.\n\n---\n\n**On the meal plan and keto:**\n\nI'm not able to create a meal plan for you — that's the territory of a registered sports dietitian, and for good reason. Nutrition at your training volume is genuinely complex, and getting it wrong can undermine everything you're building.\n\nWhat I *can* share is some context on the fat adaptation question, if that's useful — because it's a topic that comes up a lot in marathon circles and the picture is more nuanced than the headlines suggest. Would you like me to walk through what the evidence actually shows, and how it relates to your specific goal of 3:15?\n\n---\n\n**What I *can* help with right now:**\n\nYour energy issues on long runs are something we can look at from a training and fueling-*timing* angle — things like when you're eating relative to your runs, and what you're taking in during them. That's coaching territory, and it might be contributing more than you'd expect.\n\nWhat does your current routine look like on long run mornings — timing of your last meal, and what (if anything) you're taking in during the run itself?"
        }
      ],
